abstract: LONDON, Feb. 1. -- Discount rates were firm during the past week at 11 3/4 to 1 1/4. The cheapness of money led to an increase of the foreign drain of bullion which was barely balanced by the return of currency from the provinces and the distribution of dividends. Signs of a reduction of bankers' balances, combined with shortening supplies of floating capital in the markets, render a further drop of money rates impossible.

abstract: OTTAWA, Ontario, Feb. 3. -- As intimated in THE TIMES two months ago, Sir John Macdonald has dissolved Parliament. The elections will be held on March 5. Sir Charles Tupper, Canadian High Commissioner in England, and the Hon. C.C. Colby, President of the Privy Council, are due in New-York to-morrow from England. They will take part in the campaign, which will be inaugurated by a Conservative demonstration in Toronto next week.

abstract: ALBANY, Feb. 4. -- The Assembly accomplished a much-needed reform this morning. Heretofore it has been the custom for canal appropriation bills to be introduced by members who were governed by selfish and political motives. On Friday last the Canal Committee reported favorably five measures aggregating $37,600. As a matter of fact, that committee was not entitled to consider any one of these measures, as they unquestionably belonged to the Ways and Means Committee.

abstract: ALBANY, Feb. 7. -- A storm in every respect similar to that which paralyzed New-York's telegraphic and telephonic communication began here at sundown. A heavy wet snow fell, and by 8 o'clock telegraph and telephone poles all over the city were down. The Hudson River Telephone Company thus far is the greatest sufferer. Cable boxes high up on telephone poles burned up with pretty effect, and wires coming together threw off bright flashes of light.

abstract: The Jury which, under Coroner Levy, is investigating the accident in the Grand Central Station tunnel last Friday, continued its work yesterday. Three important points were brought out. The first was that the block system of signaling in vogue in the tunnel is not infallible. The second was that the liability of accidents, in consequence of the imperfect operation of the signals, would be greatly lessened if the tunnel was properly lighted.
